  "published": "2025-01-03",
  "runtimeMin": 124,
  "format": "Amanda Dobbins is back from maternity leave, and the first hour is a catch-up: where the Best Picture race actually stands (Wicked keeps rising and neither of them can stand it), Sean's physical-media habit, what their kids have been watching, and Amanda's line-by-line notes on Sean's year-end list. Then they announce 25 for ’25 (a countdown of their favorite films of the century, one per filmmaker, rolling out after the Oscars) and run all fifteen Golden Globes categories, splitting on eight of them.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The State of the Best Picture Race",
      "note": "Amanda's first discussion point",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Wicked",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Both dislike it: boring, dark to look at, choreography stuck somewhere between Broadway and Step Up. Sean concedes it's becoming the front-runner anyway and vows to throw a tantrum. Ariana Grande is the exception they'll defend."
        },
        {
          "title": "Anora",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Sean's favorite film of the year, though he senses the long-presumed front-runner is now getting the 'let's find another angle' treatment."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Brutalist",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Sean's galaxy-brain theory of the night is that the Globes go all-in on Brady Corbet. Amanda has a ticket at the Vista and keeps deferring judgment until she sees it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Emilia Pérez",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Amanda watched to the end without knowing what happened; Sean calls the writing appalling at times. It's a Mexican story from a French director with American stars, and its footing in the international race is 'funky.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Dune: Part Two",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "One of Sean's five favorites of the year; eligible for score at the Globes but not the Oscars."
        },
        {
          "title": "Nickel Boys",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Another of Sean's top five, held for a theater viewing; he thinks it's trending but hard to sit through and harder to stream."
        },
        {
          "title": "A Complete Unknown",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Sean is lower on it than Chris and Mallory ('barely a movie'), but a good platform for the songs and for Chalamet."
        },
        {
          "title": "A Different Man",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Amanda caught it before her son was born and liked it; Sebastian Stan is up for it in comedy/musical."
        },
        {
          "title": "Nosferatu",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "On Amanda's to-watch list; friends pitch it to her as a gothic romance with scares."
        },
        {
          "title": "Gladiator II",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Amanda saw it solo at 10 a.m. and found it sloppy (everyone seemed to be acting in a different room), but agrees Denzel Washington carries it, and thinks the show was too hard on Paul Mescal."
        },
        {
          "title": "Harriet",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Cited as Cynthia Erivo in her serious, grave register: good work in a film Sean doesn't rate."
        },
        {
          "title": "Widows",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "Erivo's tenacity and focus, the mode Sean thinks is miscast in Wicked."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The Break: Physical Media and the Kids' Watchlist",
      "note": "collector brain, Paddington, and the live-action Disney chain",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Wages of Fear",
          "year": 1953,
          "note": "Sean's example of restoration paying off: the 4K looks far better than it ever did on TCM in 1999."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Sting",
          "year": 1973,
          "note": "The oldest film streaming on Netflix in the US, which Sean reads as a scandal: 50 years of Hollywood before it, unavailable."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hundreds of Beavers",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Bobby name-checked its boutique Blu-ray release, alarming Amanda that the collecting bug is spreading."
        },
        {
          "title": "Paddington",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "Knox's gateway; Amanda wept through it postpartum and joined the 'Paddington dad hive.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Paddington 2",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "Same, plus Sean's running bit about its Mission: Impossible influence: the train."
        },
        {
          "title": "Wonka",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "The household's newest Paul King obsession; Knox requests it by name."
        },
        {
          "title": "Paddington in Peru",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Coming soon, and notably not a Paul King film."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Nutcracker",
